The paper describes a design study with physician scientists, statisticians, and visualization experts to investigate disease progression pathways of certain chronic diseases. The study introduces DPVis, a tool that integrates model parameters and outcomes of HMMs into interpretable and interactive visualizations. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category, as it focuses on designing a tool for medical experts to interpret and interact with disease progression models. Additionally, the paper may also belong to the Computational Biology (cs.CB) sub-category, as it deals with disease progression modeling for chronic diseases. The paper also involves machine learning techniques such as Hidden Markov Models (HMMs), which may place it in the Statistical Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents visualizations to explore disease progression patterns, which may also place it in the Information Visualization (cs.SI) sub-category.
